The better world is already here.
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to exploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the last decades results in more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
On the other hand, the optimists claim that everything will get better—the human health, the standard of living, the environmental quality, and so on.
Their opponents see them as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, supposedly solving all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is actually getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists from around the world by developing an assessment list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender relations, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – economists have all answered the same question: What were the relative costs of this problem each year from 1900 to 2013, including projections up to 2050.
Using classical economic evaluations of all factors—from deaths, health damages, and illiteracy caused by wetland destruction to increased hurricane risk due to global warming—economists outline the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the extent of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider gender inequality.
Fundamentally, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the world's workforce were women.
What are the losses that have arisen from this small share?
Even when taking into account the higher costs due to women's education and the fact that someone has to perform unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss amounts to 7% – and is likely to decrease to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring a growing net benefit – which rises to as much as 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the drawbacks.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
A moderate warming prevents more cold-related deaths than it causes additional heat-related deaths.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to an advantage of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, equivalent to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, costs increase and benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming of the world will cause net costs, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the ranking also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in the year 1900, these costs accounted for 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will decrease to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had barely changed.
On the other hand, the magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: at that time, the world's life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and is expected to be 76 years in 2050).
The greatest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the saving of three million lives each year – more than would have been saved throughout the entire 20th century by world peace.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised a further 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to astonishing 32% of global GDP.
Today, they have decreased to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Even if the optimists are not right on all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and much more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Although they have become smaller in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved a lot.
Moreover, the ranking shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not base our view of the future on the most horrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather on objective assessments of the areas in which we can achieve the greatest improvements.
